1. Prepare Your Images
Before editing the HTML, you need to have your images ready and accessible.

Save Your Images: Put your real image files (e.g., .jpg, .png) into a folder, usually named images or assets, within the same directory as your index.html.

Example Image Names:

hero-showcase.jpg (for the featured campaign)

mahdi-hasan-profile.jpg (for the about section)

project1.jpg, project2.jpg, etc. (for the project cards)

2. Replace the Hero Section Placeholder
The Hero section's featured project image is currently a div with a solid color/gradient and a symbol.

Locate the Code
Find the following block within the <section id="home" class="hero"> tag:

HTML

<div class="hero-project">
    <div class="project-showcase-image">
        </div>
    <div class="project-showcase-text">
        </div>
</div>
The Change
Replace the entire empty div with the class project-showcase-image with an <img> tag pointing to your image file. You can remove the comments and the placeholder div.

HTML

<div class="hero-project">
    <img src="images/hero-showcase.jpg" alt="Featured Campaign Success Example" class="project-showcase-image-real" style="object-fit: cover; border-radius: 15px; width: 100%; height: 280px;">
    <div class="project-showcase-text">
        <h3 class="project-showcase-title">Featured Campaign Success</h3>
        <p class="project-showcase-desc">My latest multi-channel marketing campaign that increased brand awareness by 40% across key demographics while optimizing trade partnerships and field activation strategies.</p>
    </div>
</div>
Note: You may need to adjust the CSS style (like object-fit: cover;) if your image doesn't display correctly within the container's dimensions.

3. Replace the About Section (Profile Image) Placeholder
The profile image is also a div styled to be a colored circle with a symbol.

Locate the Code
Find the following line within the <section id="about" class="about"> tag:

HTML

<div class="profile-image"></div>
The Change
Replace this div with an <img> tag.

HTML

<div class="about-content">
    <img src="images/mahdi-hasan-profile.jpg" alt="Mahdi Hasan Profile Picture" class="profile-image-real" style="width: 300px; height: 300px; border-radius: 50%; object-fit: cover; margin: 0 auto; box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(26, 26, 26, 0.15); transition: transform 0.3s ease; border: 4px solid rgba(26, 26, 26, 0.1);">
    <div class="about-text">
        </div>
</div>
Note: The inline style added above mimics the original div's styling (circular shape, size, shadows) to ensure consistency.

4. Replace Project Card Placeholders
Each project card has a placeholder image area.

Locate the Code
For each project card (inside <div class="project-card">), find the line:

HTML

<div class="project-image icon-rocket"></div>
or

HTML

<div class="project-image icon-store"></div>
(The class will change based on the project, like icon-rocket, icon-store, etc.)

The Change
Replace that placeholder div with an <img> tag pointing to the project's visual.

Original Project 1 Example:

HTML

<div class="project-card">
    <div class="project-image icon-rocket"></div> <div class="project-content">
        </div>
</div>
Modified Project 1 Example:

HTML

<div class="project-card">
    <img src="images/project1.jpg" alt="Image of National Product Launch Campaign" class="project-image-real" style="width: 100%; height: 200px; object-fit: cover;">
    <div class="project-content">
        <h3 class="project-title">National Product Launch Campaign</h3>
        </div>
</div>
Repeat this replacement for all six project cards, updating the src attribute for each one (e.g., images/project2.jpg, images/project3.jpg, etc.).

5. (Optional but Recommended) Update CSS
To keep your code clean, you should add new classes to your CSS and remove the old placeholder styling.

Add New CSS Classes
Add these new styles within your existing <style> block to ensure your new <img> tags inherit the look of their containers:

CSS

/* New styles for the real images */
.project-showcase-image-real {
    /* Retain original dimensions and rounding for the hero image */
    width: 100%;
    height: 280px;
    border-radius: 15px;
    object-fit: cover; /* Ensures image fills container without distortion */
}

.profile-image-real {
    /* Retain original dimensions, rounding, and styling for the profile image */
    width: 300px;
    height: 300px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    margin: 0 auto;
    box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(26, 26, 26, 0.15);
    transition: transform 0.3s ease;
    border: 4px solid rgba(26, 26, 26, 0.1);
}

.profile-image-real:hover {
    /* Retain hover effect */
    transform: scale(1.05);
    box-shadow: 0 25px 50px rgba(26, 26, 26, 0.2);
}

.project-image-real {
    /* Retain original dimensions for project cards */
    width: 100%;
    height: 200px;
    object-fit: cover; /* Ensures image fills container without distortion */
}
If you use these new CSS classes, you can remove the inline style="..." attributes added in the previous steps for cleaner HTML.
